FYI Heard that the SCSC were looking for information on what the high impact journals were.

See below for links to Nucleus and attached email that summarises the HI journals.

Thanks

Diane

 

From: Hatton, Diane 
Sent: 24 April 2020 11:08
To: Bright, Helen <helen.bright@astrazeneca.com>; Dibben, Oliver <oliver.dibben@astrazeneca.com>; Chapman, David <david.chapman@astrazeneca.com>; Huson, Claire <claire.huson@astrazeneca.com>; Craig, Daniel <daniel.craig@astrazeneca.com>; Lockhart, Robert  <robert.lockhart@astrazeneca.com>
Cc: Cheeks, Matthew <matthew.cheeks@astrazeneca.com>
Subject: Information on High Impact Publications

 

Link to Nucleus Page:

https://azusgb01--cms.visualforce.com/apex/Main?sname=Intranet&name=IMED-Publications#/

Where can I find information on impact factors?

The impact factors for each year are released in July of the following year. For example, in the first half of 2018, the latest available  IFs are from 2016; after July, the 2017 IFs become available. Therefore, any retrospective analysis of publications that is done after the database is updated each year will reflect the most current JCR IFs available, which may alter the ranking in previous  metric reports.

Link to table of impact factors Click  here for our master journal list with High Impact/High Quality/Other categories

Click  here for our publication tracking principles

 

An impact factor of 15 and above is defined as high impact, but note that sister journals of Cell and Nature qualify as high impact even though they  are below an impact factor of 15. This also seems to include iScience which is new.

Diane 

 

Diane Hatton PhD

Senior Director, R&D

