FYI

Is the SCSC going to have any role in driving delivery of HI publications or is this being driven at the functional level. In case you haven't come across it, please see below for more information on HI journals.

Thanks!

Diane



From: Hatton, Diane
Sent: 27 February 2020 15:48
To: Cheeks, Matthew <matthew.cheeks@astrazeneca.com>; Venkat, Raghavan <VenkatR@MedImmune.com>; Dunn, Sarah <sarah.dunn@astrazeneca.com>; Ahuja, Sanjeev <sanjeev.ahuja@astrazeneca.com>; Berge, Mark <mark.berge@astrazeneca.com>; Bleckwenn, Nicole <nicole.bleckwenn@astrazeneca.com>; Daramola, Lekan <lekan.daramola@astrazeneca.com>; Qu, Limin <limin.qu@astrazeneca.com>; Schmelzer, Albert <albert.schmelzer@astrazeneca.com>
Subject: FYI High Impact Publications



Hello Everyone

I have found information on nucleus relating to HI (high impact) publications. There are a few below IF 15 that still qualify as HI that maybe relevant for CCFS.

Eg, iScience, Nature protocols, Trends in Biotechnology (for a review article). More information on publications can be found on the nucleus page<https://azusgb01--cms.visualforce.com/apex/Main?sname=Intranet&name=IMED-Publications#/> - the HI list can be found under the FAQ section.

I don't know what manuscripts are planned for this year in the different CCFS teams, but for some of them it might be worth considering aiming for a HI journal in the first instance?

Any suggestions welcome.

Thanks

Diane



